Friendship lies at the heart of the struggle towards the success of this challenge.
A recent study of more than 2000 high school students with symptoms of depression concluded that if the patient is surrounded by enough friends “with a healthy disposition”, his chances of recovery are doubled.
To the same extent, for people who are not depressed, a circle of healthy mental friends reduces to half the probability of mental disorders.
Of course, for friendship to take effect, it must first be accessible.
In this era of communication dominated by social networks, where emphasis is placed on style rather than substance, the immediate nature of the response often takes priority before contact with meaning.
Our digital lives have doubled the need to create the appearance of a strong personality, open to fun and success, even if in reality isolation is the one that dominates.
This superficial success is dominated by what psychologists call extrinsic values; money, image, social status, all at the cost of intrinsic values - our inner desire for personal development and friendship - which further affects our mental health.
The billionaire inventor of a video game recently explained that money does not even buy happiness.
The beauty of the Friends series was that it directed attention to this idea.
The characters were not defined by the job but by their own personality, which they showed by interacting as friends.
The humor of Joey and Chandler's frequent hugs, the moments when they look at football in the comfortable photollies and Ross's passion for Rachel came from the fact that men can be associated with this situation, even though they often avoid exploring their feelings completely.
As a social worker explained to me: ..."my role in listening to people who tend to commit suicide and depressed showed how even the smallest interactions with friends can make a difference."
Often, the people calling us don't feel able to talk to friends.
The old saying to manage yourself is powerful, as is the feeling of being perceived as weak if you talk openly about problems.
Friends is one of the series that comes to mind when I try to offer several long-term psychological adaptation mechanisms.
The series highlighted the small moments of friendship between men.
As much as it helps the objective, external intervention through the telephone, people reached in times of despair, long-term support comes from family and close friends.
Thus, if you are attending this weekend at FriendsFest organized by Comedy Central, with the complete play of filming dishes to celebrate the event, why not invite your friends to a coffee in Central Perk.
Or, even better, if you see someone alone in Starbucks, smile and greet.
You never know what difference your friendship might make.
