The government approved, Wednesday, "National Strategy on Immigration for the period 2015-2018" and "The Action Plan for the current year", documents considered to be "an additional step in Romania's efforts to modernise the immigration management process on national territory", according to a press release.
The mentioned source shows that the strategy aims to manage the effective phenomenon of immigration, including general strategic objectives, specific objectives and action guidelines that reflect European-level policies adapted to national realities.
Given the problems faced by the States of the immediate vicinity of Romania, steps are being taken to manage the unity and consistency of situations determined by the possible influx of illegal immigrants into the territory of Romania, generated by situations of political, social, economic or military crisis.
"Roman authorities will contribute to the creation of a flexible admission system, but at the same time, they will pay special attention to citizens from countries with potential migrationists or which can affect national security," adds the mentioned source.
The strategy identifies a number of factors that can influence immigration and asylum, including maintaining the conflict in Syria, reactivating the conflict in Iraq, maintaining an unstable situation in the border areas of Romania (Ukraine, Transnistria), perpetuating and increasing the intensity of the Israeli-Palestinian armed conflict.
On the other hand, the document sets out a few general strategic objectives related to immigration, such as: the promotion of legal migration, more rigorous controls on the legality of the seat of third-country nationals on the territory of Romania and the appropriate application of removal measures and restrictive measures, the improvement of the national asylum system.
The national strategy also includes specific objectives relevant to the transposition and implementation of the general strategic objectives.
These include: facilitating access to the territory of Romania of third-country nationals who respond to the needs of occupation of the workforce, promoting access of third-country nationals to Romanian higher education institutions for areas and professions identified as deficit.
